 England":"Bold, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1443–1491":"1443–1491","1429–1509":"1429–1509","1438–1460":"1438–1460","1478–1528":"1478–1528","1389–1456":"1389–1456","1410–1474":"1410–1474","ABT 1456":"about 1456","1460":"1460","1491":"1491","04 Mar 1474":"4 March 1474","1478":"1478","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1474":"1474","1509":"1509","1528":"1528","1429":"1429","about 1460":"about 1460","1438":"1438","Puddington, Cheshire, England":"Puddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bold, Lancashire, England":"Bold, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Massey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Massy</i>, a pet form of   Matthew  . Compare   Mace  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one or more of several places in Normandy, such as Macey (Manche), Massy (Seine-Maritime), Macé-sur-Orne (Orne), and La Ferté Macé (Orne).","English: variant of <b>Marsay</b> (see   Marcey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mace","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Masse</i>, probably a shortened form of <i>Matthew</i> (compare   Massey   and   Massett  ) or possibly of   Thomas  .","French and Breton (<b>Macé</b>): from the French personal name <i>Macé</i>, a vernacular form of   Mathieu   ‘Matthew’. Compare   Masse   5 and   Maze   3.","French (<b>Macé</b>): habitational name from Macé or La Ferté-Macé in Orne, the former so named from Gallo-Roman <i>Macciacum</i> (from the personal name <i>Maccius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>), the latter from the personal name <i>Macé</i> (see 2 above)."]},{"name":"Massie","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeen): variant of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Marsee","meanings":["English: altered form of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Massee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Germain.","Possibly an altered form of English   Massey  .","French (<b>Massée</b>): from the feminine form of <b>Massé</b> (see   Masse  ). This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Massa","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Antonio, Silvio, Annamarie, Biagio, Caesar, Carmela, Dante, Elisabetta, Ennio.","Italian: habitational name from any of various places called Massa, for example Massa Lubrense or Massa di Somma, both in Naples province, or Masse d'Albe in Aquila, all named from medieval Latin <i>massa</i> ‘farm, estate’ (from Latin <i>massa</i> ‘mass, lump, pile’, Greek <i>maza</i>). This surname is also found in southern France (see   Massey   5)."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Macey","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  .","Americanized form of Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Macej</b> or <b>Mačej</b> and Polish   Maciej  , derivatives of the Latin personal name <i>Matthaeus</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Masey","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Macy","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":12,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas de Massey was born in 1443, in Coddington, Cheshire, England, his father, Esq. Hugh Massey of Coddington, was 54 and his mother, Anne Bold, was 33. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Bold. He died in 1491, in Coddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1443–1491":"1443–1491","1429–1509":"1429–1509","1438–1460":"1438–1460","1478–1528":"1478–1528","1389–1456":"1389–1456","1410–1474":"1410–1474","ABT 1456":"umbes 1456","1460":"1460","1491":"1491","04 Mar 1474":"4. märts 1474","1478":"1478","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1474":"1474","1509":"1509","1528":"1528","1429":"1429","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1438":"1438","Puddington, Cheshire, England":"Puddington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bold, Lancashire, England":"Bold, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","En